{{Alt Class|ent=3|ext=3|env=1|no=168}}<Center>[[Level 168]], colloquially referred to as ''“Too Many Floors,”'' is recognized as the 169th documented level within [[Backrooms Wiki|the Backrooms]].</center>
== <Div class="styled-quote">Description</div> ==
{{Blurimage|file=-2.2-5.webp|caption=<code>Golf?</code>}}
[[Level 168]] is an immense, non-Euclidean complex consisting of endless lobby rooms, corridors, and strange stairwells. Illumination is provided by subtle, humming fluorescent fixtures unevenly installed throughout the environment.

The primary connective tissue of [[Level 168]] is formed by long, curvy hallways with aged carpeting or, less commonly, spotless white tiling. These segments turn infinitely, and usually loop back on themselves. Paintings, mainly gold-framed and featuring blank white canvases, line the hallways and contribute to the sterile, uncanny ambiance. Some corridors contain uncarpeted flooring or unfinished structural steel, which suggests portions of the level are still in a state of metaphysical construction.

The lobby rooms are approximately 500 square feet in area and feature green carpeting, beige pillars, modern table-and-chair sets, and, bizarrely, miniature golf installations. These spaces exert a subtle memetic influence, reportedly instilling an overwhelming urge to engage in either chess or mini-golf. Individuals who submit to this impulse usually find themselves unable to leave voluntarily.
{{Blurimage|file=-2.2-3.webp|caption=<code>Where am I?</code>|align=left}}
While rarely seen, some individuals report that undocumented passive entities occasionally appear and quietly play chess within these rooms. Several doors are located at the rear of each lobby, with some leading to deeper levels or hostile environments. It is strongly recommended to exit through the same door used upon entry.

Interspersed throughout the level are vast, sterile corridors referred to as open halls, tile-floored expanses broken only by supporting pillars. These areas are accessible via select doors in the standard hallway sections. Individuals usually enter through a furnished vestibule containing a sofa, a fish tank, flowerpots, and portraits of various well-known figures. Ambient buzzing, similar to [[Level 0]]'s, is omnipresent.

Beyond this room lies a cavernous and tiled expanse. To the right, a chamber of pure darkness exists, intermittently inhabited by aggressive entities. At the far end, a wooden door marked with the current floor number offers passage back into the broader labyrinth.
{{Blurimage|file=-2.2-4.webp|caption=<code>Where am I ascending to?</code>}}
Traveling far enough through the corridors leads to the '''Infinite Spiral''', a unique architectural zone that offers access to several floors spiraling upward or downward. This region is significantly safer, with minimal presence of entities. Numerous cubicles populate the area, and each contains retro and modern office furnishings: a desk, swivel chair, and obsolete computer. Vending machines dispensing [[Object 1|Almond Water]] and [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms]]-branded soda are sporadically placed throughout.

[[Level 168]] features recurring staircase complexes, each comprising infinitely high flights with a large number of steps per floor. These stairwells exhibit off-white walls, brown carpeting, and metallic railings. At the base of each new level, a red door displays the floor number engraved in a gold plaque. Electrical outlets are occasionally present but are considered volatile and hazardous due to reports of spontaneous combustion.

The stairwells exhibit a persistent, acrid odor of burnt wiring lingering in the air, likely stemming from faulty or unstable electrical outlets in the walls. Lighting in these areas is prone to sudden failure, resulting in brief but unnerving blackouts. The walls themselves are occasionally found to be discolored, normally appearing in a faint pink color.

It is speculated that the staircases terminate after exactly one hundred floors, beyond which no further vertical movement is possible.

== <Div class="styled-quote">Entities</div> ==
[[Level 168]] contains hostile entities such as [[Entity 3|Smilers]], [[Entity 5|Clumps]], [[Entity 10|Skin-Stealers]], [[Entity 36|Lighters]], and [[Entity 69|Lightlurkers]]. Fortunately, their distribution is sparse; each floor typically hosts three entities. The level's vast spatial scale significantly dilutes the immediate threat posed by these entities, although caution is essential.

=== <Div class="styled-quote">Trepidovenator hal. / False-Friend</div> ===
{{Blurimage|file=Entiity-2.webp|caption=<code>My friend?</code>|align=left}}
'''False-Friend''', also scientifically known as ''"Trepidovenator hal.,"'' is a formidable and psychologically manipulative entity encountered predominantly in the darker expanses of [[Level 168]]'s massive halls and serpentine hallways.

The '''False-Friend''' is a tall, emaciated humanoid creature with an unnaturally long frame and sinewy musculature, which are built for speed and strength. Its skin is coarse and dark brown. This entity features an aged dirty piece of cloth wrapped around its waist.

Its feet is identical to a digitigrade animal's, which are also built for rapid movement across uneven ground. The creature has razor-sharp claws that are capable of tearing through most materials with ease. Its mouth is disturbingly wide, filled with rows of jagged, predatory teeth. Most unsettlingly, its face is partially obscured by fragments of human skeletal parts; jawbones, cheekbones, and cranium shards crudely affixed, as if it were a protective mask, which gives it a grotesque and deathly visage.

Its behavior is characterized by escalating aggression in response to proximity, making it particularly dangerous during close encounters. From a distance of over 200 feet, it moves slowly, its mouth open and its expression glazed. Around 100 feet, it begins to run, grows taller and more alert; its claws lengthen, and its eyes glow red. At 50 feet, its eyes bleed into a glowing blue, and it emits a strange, quiet scream able to attract nearby entities. At 15 feet, the entity exerts a strong psychological effect that convinces the target it is a trusted companion. This causes most victims to stop fleeing, allowing the False-Friend to catch up and kill them.

=== <div class="styled-quote">Sapomorphus / Food Mimic</div> ===
'''Sapomorphus''', or informally known as ''"Food Mimic,"'' is a small, three-legged mimicry-based entity known for its deceptive appearance and unsettling mobility. Standing no taller than a soccer ball, the creature possesses a spherical main body supported by three jointed, sinewy legs. When not camouflaged, '''Sapomorphus''' moves with impressive speed, scuttling in abrupt, insect-like motions and making subtle squelching sounds.

The entity’s defining trait is its advanced mimicry ability. It can morph into the appearance of large, visually tasty food dishes, such as roasted meats, decorated cakes, or steaming noodle bowls. However, its mimicry is not perfect; the false dishes always have a unnatural roundness, which sets them apart from authentic meals upon close inspection. Individuals may also notice subtle pulsing beneath the surface, or faint movement where toppings should be.

Despite its convincing visual disguise, the '''Food Mimic''' cannot conceal its odor. All transformations have a stench of rotting flesh mixed with moist, radiating heat, reminiscent of spoiled food. This trait, however, can sometimes be overlooked in areas where decay is common.

Atop the creature’s body is a small, recessed mouth cavity, which is usually hidden during mimicry but slightly visible to observant individuals. Within this orifice exists a thin, needle-like stinger, which it uses to inject neurotoxic fluids into victims who approach too closely or attempt to eat the disguised body. These fluids cause disorientation, nausea, and localized paralysis within minutes.

When not actively mimicking food, '''Sapomorphus''' is highly mobile. It prefers dark or cluttered areas for repositioning and usually retreats when spotted. It only engages when confident its disguise will fool its target. After stinging a victim, the entity usually flees, allowing its neurotoxins to weaken the host before it returns to feed.

== <div class="styled-quote">Colonies, Bases, & Outposts</div> ==
=== <div class="styled-quote">The Community of [[Level 168]]</div> ===
* Neutral group with 14 members.
* Based in the center of Floor 202.
* Well-stocked with [[Object 1|Almond Water]].
* Armed with various weapons, including MEG-supplied guns.

=== <div class="styled-quote">Escape Omega (Does Not Exist Anymore)</div> ===
* Group of 7 wanderers focused on escaping the level.
* Occupies all of Floor 217.
* Decently supplied with essentials.
* Welcomes anyone who is willing to aid in their escape.
* Formed by individuals with traumatic encounters.

== <div class="styled-quote">Entrances & Exits</div> ==
=== <div class="styled-quote">Entrances</div> ===
* Entering an unnaturally large building in [[Level 163]], leads directly into this level.
* No-Clipping into a white wall in [[Level 164]], teleports here.
* A rare glitching golfing ground in [[Level 153]], transports one to this level.

=== <div class="styled-quote">Exits</div> ===
* Wandering far enough may rarely trigger a transition the level into [[Level 169]].
* Opening an old door in 124th floor may open to [[Level 172]].
* Breaking through window that shows the other side as a river, directs to [[Level 173]].
* Glitching into the stairs, leads one to [[Level 807]].
* [[The Void|No-clipping]] through a strangely positioned orange wall within the stairways leads one to [[Level 677]].

